## 3. Proposed Flow — Structural Walkthrough

```
User (developer/associate)
  │
  ├─ [submits change] → PUT /serviceJobs/{jobName}
  │                      POST /serviceJobs
  │                      (or any other "update" API endpoint)
  │
  ▼
Backend Service (intercepting layer)
  │
  ├─ Does NOT call update#moqui.service.job.ServiceJob directly
  │
  ├─ Instead: creates ServiceJobEditAppl record {
  │     applicationData: <JSON payload of proposed changes>,
  │     action: "updateServiceJob",
  │     actionType: <points to HTML artifact/template>,
  │     applicationDateTime: now,
  │     createdDateTime: now,
  │     statusId: "PENDING",
  │     requestedByUserId: currentUser,
  │     approvedByUserId: null
  │   }
  │
  ├─ Sends email notification to Account Manager with review link
  │
  ▼
Reviewer Dashboard (HTML artifact)
  │
  ├─ Loads ServiceJobEditAppl by ApplicationRequestId (PK)
  ├─ Calls 2 APIs:
  │   ├─ [GET] current live state of the ServiceJob entity
  │   └─ [GET] applicationData JSON from ServiceJobEditAppl
  ├─ Renders side-by-side JSON diff
  │
  ├─ Reviewer clicks Approve / Reject
  │
  ▼
Backend: approve#request wrapper service
  │
  ├─ Input: ApplicationRequestId
  ├─ Fetches: applicationData + action from ServiceJobEditAppl
  ├─ Calls: update#ServiceJob (the actual DB-persisting service)
  ├─ Updates: ServiceJobEditAppl.statusId → "APPROVED" / "REJECTED"
  └─ (Optional) Notifies requester of decision
```

This flow is **correct in structure**. The pattern maps 1:1 to `AiToolCallRequest` from `moqui-ai` — a proven HITL gate pattern already present in this codebase.

